@node intro "A short introduction to NewStuff"

  NewStuff was born one day, when, for the millionth time, I had just
  downloaded something, and couldn't find it when looking through my downloads
  directory.  The file was named something like xrd-v433_prev.lha, which isn't
  exactly descriptive, and so it didn't jump out as being anything important.
  I started checking each archive, looking for the one I wanted, when I
  realized I could use the powerful "list" command to list new files.  It
  wasn't long after that that I thought of writing a program to do this
  automatically.

  NewStuff is a small commodity that sits in the background, and keeps a close
  watch on your downloads directory (or any directory that you choose).  When
  a new file arrives, it makes a hard link from that file to directories
  called Session and Recent.  Now your new file is available in your Session
  directory, and you don't have to look through pages of other files to find
  it!

  The same applies to the Recent directory.  New files appear here for as long
  as you like, and then once they become old enough, the links are removed
  and they are only available in your downloads directory.

  Because NewStuff uses links to do all this, you only ever have one copy
  of each file on your hard drive.  The files in Session and Recent are the
  same as the one in your download directory, so any changes you make to this
  file will be reflected in the others as well.

@endnode

