@node require "What you need to run this huge program"

  NewStuff Requirements:

  * Any Amiga running Kickstart 2.1 or higher, with a battery backed
    up clock

  * 1 meg of free RAM should be more than enough

  * A hard drive is strongly suggested, NewStuff wouldn't make much sense
    on a floppy!

  * A partition using a filesystem that supports hard links (see @{"Installation" link install}
    for more on this!)

  NewStuff has been tested (successfully) on these machines:

  A1200 Kickstart 3.0  68020-14/882-25 2M Chip 8M Fast
  A1200 Kickstart 3.0  68030-50/882-50 2M Chip 16M Fast
  A500  Kickstart 3.1  68020-14/881-14 1M Chip 6M Fast
  A500  Kickstart 2.1  68000-7         1M Chip 3.5M Fast

@endnode

@node install "Installation Instructions"

  Although the installation of NewStuff is very simple, you must be sure
  that your hard drive partition is using a filesystem that supports
  hard links.

  The standard 2.1 and 3.0 FFS filesystems appear to work just fine.
  PFS2 also has been reported to work.

  3.0's Directory Cache filesystem @{b}may@{ub} cause problems, but I know of
  at least one person using this with NewStuff without trouble.  I've also
  tested NewStuff on a DCFS floppy, and it worked perfectly, so chances are
  it's not a problem.  The only reason I am unsure is that I had a problem
  with it in the early stages of NewStuff (when it used soft links) and I was
  using DCFS.  It was a fairly harmless unvalidated partition, which took
  only a few minutes to fix.

  I haven't had a single problem since then, but I've also changed to
  standard FFS. :)  Please @{"contact" link contact} me if you are using NewStuff
  with another filesystem, or if you're using it with DCFS, so I can add
  these filesystems to the list.

  Now that I've scared off half of you, here's what you need to do:

  1)  Make two new directories that will be your Session and Recent
      directories.  Don't put any of your own files in either of these
      directories, NewStuff will handle them on its own, and will
      delete files at will. :)
      These directories @{b}must@{ub} be on the same partition as your
      watched directory.

  2)  Move NewStuff to the WBStartup drawer on your boot partition.

  3)  Configure NewStuff (see @{"Configuration" link config}).

@endnode

@node config "Setting up NewStuff"

  Once NewStuff has been @{"installed" link install}, you should set the tooltypes.  They are:

  WATCH = <directory>    The directory to scan for new files, i.e.
                         Work:Downloads/.

  RECENT = <directory>   The directory in which to place files that have
                         arrived in the past few days.

  SESSION = <directory>  The directory in which to place files that have
                         arrived since the last boot.

    These three directories must be on the same partition, or the links will
    fail (and NewStuff will not work).

    Also, these three directories must be different, ie don't use the same
    directory for Session and Recent, or Session and Watch, etc.


  AGE = <# of days>      The number of days to keep files in the Recent
                         directory.
                         NewStuff will assume 3 days if this is omitted.

  USEWINDOW = YES/NO     Whether or not NewStuff will open its window when it
                         starts.
                         The default is YES.

  AUTODELETE = YES/NO    Whether or not NewStuff will automatically delete
                         files when you delete a file from the Recent or
                         Session directory.
                         The default is NO.

                         See @{"Usage" link usage} for more details on this feature.

  VIEWERS = <file>       The file containing filetypes and viewers to use to
                         display them.  Each line of this text file should
                         contain the text to match in the filename, followed
                         by a vertical pipe (|), and the command to run.
                         Use %s to place the name of the new file in the
                         command string, eg:

                         .txt|sys:utilities/Multiview %s
                         .mod|work:music/modplayer/modplayer %s
                         .lha|echo "%s has arrived!" > CON:

                         An example file has also been included, called
                         "viewers".


  SESSIONASSIGN = <name> The name of the assign to create for the Session
                         directory.
                         The assign will be removed if NewStuff exits.
                         This defaults to ".Session".

  RECENTASSIGN  = <name> The name of the assign to create for the Recent
                         directory.
                         The assign will be removed if NewStuff exits.
                         This defaults to, you guessed it, ".Recent".

                         If you're wondering, the "." at the beginning of the
                         assign causes it to appear at the top of the list in
                         a file requester.
@endnode

@node usage "General Usage"


  Once NewStuff has been installed and set up, it should be fairly invisible
  in day to day use.  It's a commodity, so it can be removed and disabled
  as usual.

  Here's how it all works:

  @{b}Startup@{ub}

  When NewStuff starts, it first deletes all files from the Session directory.
  Then, it scans the Watch directory, and adds any files that qualify as
  recent to the Recent directory.  It will show these files' names in its
  window, if the @{"USEWINDOW tooltype" link config} is set to YES.  Finally, it removes any
  older files from the Recent directory, and begins watching the Watch
  directory.


  @{b}Arrival of new files@{ub}

  When a new file is detected in the Watch directory, NewStuff makes a link
  from it to the Recent and Session directories.  If the filename contains
  a string matching one found in the viewers file (see @{"Configuration" link config}
  and the VIEWERS tooltype) then NewStuff will launch the tool for this file.


  @{b}Deleting Files@{ub}

  NewStuff supports deleting of any of the three copies of a file.
  When you delete a file from the Watch directory, both of its links will
  be removed, from Session and Recent.

  If you delete a file from the Session directory or the Recent directory,
  NewStuff will also delete it from Watch and Recent, or Watch and Session,
  respectively.

  If you have set the @{"AUTODELETE tooltype" link config} to NO, then NewStuff will
  ask you before doing this.  A requester will open, giving you three choices:

  "Yes" will remove all copies of the file everywhere.

  "Yes to All" is the same as "Yes", but if NewStuff encounters any further
   deleted files, it will not prompt before deleting them.

   NOTE:  Depending on the order in which you delete files, NewStuff might
          still prompt you even if you do click "Yes to All".

  "No" will not remove any of the other copies of the file, although
   the one that you have just removed will still be gone.

  @{b}Renaming Files@{ub}

  Renaming files does no harm, but NewStuff will not recognize the change
  right away.  If you rename a file in your Watch directory, the links
  will retain their original names.  The next time you boot, NewStuff
  will notice that the original file has disappeared, and will ask
  you before removing the link with the old name.  Then it will add
  a link for the file with the new name, and things will return to normal.


  @{b}Warning Messages@{ub}

  These requesters might appear when NewStuff detects odd files or missing
  files in one of its directories.

  @{i}"<filename> is about to be deleted from the <directory> directory!
   However, this file is not a link..."@{ui}

   This appears when NewStuff is about to delete a file from a directory,
   but it has detected that the file is not a link.  This can happen a
   number of different ways, but probably the most likely cause is
   that you've deleted the original file while NewStuff wasn't running.
   When you delete a file that has links to other files, the links
   change to normal files.

   This can also happen if you've accidentally copied a normal file into
   one of NewStuff's directories.

   In any case, this is your last chance to keep the file, so choose
   "Leave It" if you want to hang on to the file (and copy it elsewhere!).


   @{i}"<filename> is in <recent directory>, but not in <watch directory>.
   It was probably deleted while NewStuff was not running..."@{ui}

   This appears when a file appears in the Recent directory that is not
   in the Watch directory (and can sometimes appear as well as the above
   error).  As it suggests, the usual cause of this is that you deleted
   the original file from the Watch directory while NewStuff was not
   running.  It's usually safe to allow NewStuff to remove the file,
   but if in doubt, @{b}don't@{ub}!  Move the file to a safe place if you're
   unsure.
@endnode

@node tips "Some tips for getting the most out of NewStuff"

    Here are a few tips that you may find helpful:

    * Use the automatic Session and Recent assigns!  When using a file
      requester, click the "Volumes" gadget, and .Recent and .Session
      should be right there for quick access, unless you've changed
      the defaults (see @{"Configuration" link config}).

    * Leave out the icons for your Session and Recent directories on
      Workbench.  Then, especially if you have icon docks on your
      Workbench, you can easily drag and drop new files there.

    * If you use a directory manager type program, make buttons for the
      Session and Recent directories.

    Sorry, that's all I can think of for now... :)
@endnode

@node future "Future features and improvements"

  Here's a list of features you might see in future versions of NewStuff.
  Please @{"contact" link contact} me with your suggestions, they might make their
  way onto this list!

 * Some sort of notification when a new file arrives, such as speech or
   playing a sound sample (send me your ideas!)

   You @{i}could@{ui} do this using the autoview feature (see @{"Configuration" link config}),
   try something like:

   .lha|c:play16 work:samples/newfile.8svx

 * Multiple watch directories -- This one's a remote possibility, if
   you would like this feature, let me know, it might become a reality
   in a future version.

 * A GUI?  For now, NewStuff is simple enough to not really need a GUI
   for configuration, and I don't want it to become a huge, super-flexible
   mega-program. :)

@endnode

@node contact "Please send me some email!"

  You can reach me via email to @{b}ah210@chebucto.ns.ca@{ub}.

  I'd like to hear all comments about NewStuff, especially bug reports,
  suggestions, and anything of a positive nature. :)  Of course, I'll be
  glad to help with any problems you might be having, and I'm open to
  constructive criticism -- just don't expect a quick reply to the latter. :)

  I would @{b}really@{ub} appreciate it if anyone using NewStuff would send
  me a short email just so I have an idea of how many people use it.  The
  more users there are, the better motivated I'll be to improve it!

  You can also visit my page at @{b}http://chebucto.ns.ca/~ah210/Profile.html@{ub}.
  You'll find a few other projects of mine (mainly Reminder), the odd bit
  of info on NewStuff, and who knows what else...

  I look forward to hearing from you!

@endnode
